						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tdondich wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Thankfully, @rainwarrior shows the address where input loop starts.</div><br />It's really very quick to find if you know how to look for it. i.e. open a debugging emulator (e.g. Mesen/FCEUX/Nintendulator) and put a breakpoint on reads from $4016, it'll pop up right away.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">@rainwarrior -- thanks for correcting me!  I just remember that in early NES emulator days (~1996/1997), there were several games that people had to do strange quirks to get controller reads working right.  I vaguely recall values $80, $01, or $40 were somehow involved.  I don't remember context, sadly.</div><br />The values read through $4016 on a NES are normally $40 or $41. The reason why is described <a href="https://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Open_bus_behavior" class="postlink">on the wiki</a>. (There are ways to get other values too, though. This should not be hard-coded as $40 or $41, it should implement the actual open bus behaviour, which that wiki page describes.)</div>

